completions.md
     1‚Üí# The completions command
     2‚Üí
     3‚ÜíThe completions command is used to generate auto-completions for some common shells.
     4‚ÜíThis means when you type `mdbook` in your shell, you can then press your shell's auto-complete key (usually the Tab key) and it may display what the valid options are, or finish partial input.
init.md
     1‚Üí# The init command
     2‚Üí
     3‚ÜíThere is some minimal boilerplate that is the same for every new book. It's for
     4‚Üíthis purpose that mdBook includes an `init` command.
    32‚Üí#### Tip: Generate chapters from SUMMARY.md
    33‚Üí
    34‚ÜíWhen a `SUMMARY.md` file already exists, the `init` command will first parse it
    35‚Üíand generate the missing files according to the paths used in the `SUMMARY.md`.
    39‚Üí#### Specify a directory
    40‚Üí
    41‚ÜíThe `init` command can take a directory as an argument to use as the book's root
    42‚Üíinstead of the current working directory.
    48‚Üí#### `--theme`
    49‚Üí
    50‚ÜíWhen you use the `--theme` flag, the default theme will be copied into a
    51‚Üídirectory called `theme` in your source directory so that you can modify it.
    56‚Üí#### `--title`
    57‚Üí
    58‚ÜíSpecify a title for the book. If not supplied, an interactive prompt will ask for 
    59‚Üía title. 
    65‚Üí#### `--ignore`
    66‚Üí
    67‚ÜíCreate a `.gitignore` file configured to ignore the `book` directory created when [building] a book. 
    68‚ÜíIf not supplied, an interactive prompt will ask whether it should be created.
    80‚Üí#### `--force`
    81‚Üí
    82‚ÜíSkip the prompts to create a `.gitignore` and for the title for the book.
